This article is a letter from President Barack Obama to the Speaker of the House, discussing military operations in various countries in support of U.S. counterterrorism objectives. The letter explains that the U.S. continues to work with partners around the globe, focusing on areas of responsibility for the U.S. Central Command and U.S. Africa Command. The U.S. has deployed combat-equipped forces to enhance the counterterrorism capabilities and support the operations of allies. The letter provides specific information about counterterrorism deployments in Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Turkey, Somalia, Yemen, Djibouti, Libya, Niger, Cameroon, Egypt, Jordan, and Kosovo. The letter emphasizes that the U.S. remains in an armed conflict against al-Qa'ida, the Taliban, and associated forces, and that operations and deployments are ongoing. The President also highlights the success of these operations in degrading al-Qa'ida's capabilities and bringing an end to Taliban rule in Afghanistan. The letter concludes by stating that the President will direct additional measures to protect U.S. citizens and interests if necessary, and that the scope and duration of deployments cannot be determined at this time.